<HEADLINE>
<P>
REDUCING CLASS SIZES IN CALIFORNIA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I am deeply concerned and critical of Gov. Deukmejian's unwise decision to cut 
funding for the California Assessment Program (CAP). In the light of increasing 
criticism of our national education policies, we can ill afford the loss of yet 
another educational program. 
</P>
<P>
As a senior at Artesia High School, my fellow seniors and I were looking 
forward to increasing the scores for our school. We saw the CAP test and our 
school scores as a rallying point for campus pride. 
</P>
<P>
The logic in the governor's decision escapes me. I can only hope that the new 
governor will show more concern for the state's troubled schools by restoring 
funds for CAP, among other things. I can also say that Gov. Deukmejian's 
dubious abilities, demonstrated by the CAP and his handling of Proposition 98, 
have made me Democrat on state issues, while I am still Republican on national 
ones. 
</P>
<P>
EDWARD KYUNG HO KIM 
</P>
<P>
Hawaiian Gardens 
</P>
</TEXT>
