<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: TOON TALK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BETH KLEID , Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Welcome Jo Yo: Mort Walker will celebrate the 40th anniversary of his comic 
strip "Beetle Bailey" Tuesday by adding a new character to the staff at Camp 
Swampy: Japanese-American Cpl. 
</P>
<P>
Joe (Kashikoi) Yo. The character's middle name means "smart and clever" in 
Japanese. "We felt the time had come to include an Asian-American in our cast," 
Walker said. When the strip premiered on Sept. 4, 1950, the title character in 
"Beetle Bailey" was a goof-off college student; he mistakenly enlisted in the 
Army during the Korean War and has remained in the service ever since. BETH 
KLEID 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Drawing, Yo 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
